      <aside class="calc-sidebar">
        <div class="card sidebar-card">
          <h2>What are number systems?</h2>
          <p>Number systems are different ways to represent the same value using different bases. Decimal (base 10) is what we use every day. Binary (base 2) is the language of computers. Hexadecimal (base 16) is used in programming and web colours. Octal (base 8) is used in Unix file permissions.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card sidebar-card">
          <h3>Frequently asked questions</h3>
          <details>
            <summary>What is binary?</summary>
            <p>Binary is a base-2 number system that uses only 0 and 1. It is the fundamental language of all digital computers and electronic devices.</p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>What is hexadecimal used for?</summary>
            <p>Hexadecimal (hex) is used in programming to represent memory addresses, colours in web design (e.g. #FF5733) and byte values in a compact form. Each hex digit represents exactly 4 binary digits.</p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>What is 255 in binary?</summary>
            <p>255 in binary is 11111111 — eight 1s. In hexadecimal it is FF. This is why the maximum value of a single byte is 255.</p>
          </details>
        </div>
